content:
So I have some news.

After 14 amazing years at Penn, I'm moving to a unique new gig at Georgetown. Starting this semester, I'll be the McDevitt Chair of Computer Science and Law, where I'll focus on interdisciplinary research and teaching that bridges CS and law/public policy.

ICYMI: I'm no longer actively posting here, and check my Twitter DMs and mentions only very rarely. To the extent I'm on social media, I've mostly moved to Mastodon, where I can be found at: https://t.co/Q8g3FNzKwW
The bad things I'm worried about as Twitter implodes don't involve spectaular interruptions of service (though that will suck), but quiet data breaches and account compromises.

I'm not closing my account, but I'm also not posting much here any more. A much better place to find me as this place becomes an increasingly pale shadow of its former self is at https://t.co/4XD2XjNCio

As this hellsite reinstates various loathsome trolls, spare a thought for the first amendment scholars here trying in vain to explain the difference between government censorship and private moderation for the hundredth gazillion time.
Imagine thinking that the main problems and conflicts of a forum that serves hundreds of millions of people from every corner of humanity involve "inadequately hardcore engineers".
I'll definitely miss having every single thing explained to me.
Twitter, in one slde. https://t.co/tpdfVG4Hr7

Wow, this headline.

How are there no "Downfall" captions for this yet?

https://t.co/JDb1S8DhH3
Evaluating software engineers by looking at screenshots of code they've written is dumb. But if you're going to do it that way, it would be more illuminating to look at code they've *deleted*.

@see_wolff For typical users, think everything from passwords (people re-use them) to exposure to scams that exploit social connections to be more convincing.

For dissidents in repressive countries who used Twitter to organize, a lot worse than that.
The Twitter meltdown is distracting me from fully enjoying the FTX meltdown.
Numerous reports that 2FA currently isn't working here. So things seem to be going really well.
New Twitter Blue feature: at the $8 level, you're allowed to go into any Twitter data center and activate the Halon system.
Now I’m worried that my RPCs are poorly batched.
Radio nerditry: Yes, I've heard that KrakenRF pulled their passive radar code, and no, I'm not looking forward to revisiting ITAR after all these years.

Unpopular and uncomfortable election integrity reality: While BS about "hacked elections" has been most loudly amplified by the Right in the US, they have no monopoly on it. This nonsense was mostly started by (and continues to be spread by) marginal activists on the Left.
@maxrenke @alt_tag @CathyGellis No. Deceit may or may not be protected under 1A. If it’s in the service of parody, it probably is. If fraud, probably not.
@maxrenke @alt_tag @CathyGellis Parody can absolutely involve deception. See The Onion’s recent amicus brief for a good discussion of this.
I'm really done with being "nice" about election integrity mis- and disinformation.  Actually, I never started.
@AchillesLastWar @cjones47 I'll have to live with your disapproval
I'm imagining the guy who bought this website reading about Bankman-Fried making half a billion dollars disappear overnight and thinking, "amateur."
I guess all those cryptocurrency people got tired of being rich.
Even if it taxes your patience, being careful and following procedures in tallying votes is not evidence of fraud. In fact, it's the opposite of that.

Musk essentially admits here that not only is he aware that you can pay $8 to maliciously impersonate a brand for a period of time, he regards it as a valuable source of revenue.

I’d imagine any impersonated brands contemplating litigation would find that quite interesting. https://t.co/ZGebkUiN3x

As amusing as all this is to watch, Twitter remains an important source of information in crisis situations.

I worry that if there's a large scale emergency or disaster, the inability to sort out real from fake is going to cost lives.

Musk *really* needs to stop flailing.

So far this election (keeping my fingers crossed), there have been few instances of violence or intimidation of election works from election deniers. That's due in large part to herculean efforts to educate voters on how elections actually work. https://t.co/ra9VA3C49X
Tesla Blue, a new service available for a small monthly fee, gives your vehicle automatic right-of-way over Teslas that aren't part of the program.

Reminder: as partial tallies are released, candidates don't actually "take the lead" or "fall behind", in the sense that they can change the outcome by working harder. All the votes were already cast. There are already winners and losers. We just don't know who they are yet.
I'll be doing my part hitting refresh every 2.5 seconds. I hope the rest of you pitch in, too.

I don’t know what the results of today’s elections will be.

As we sort through the inevitable noise as result come in, remember two difficult truths about election security:

 - there *are* some real vulnerabilities;
 - there’s never been credible evidence of a hacked election.

@cstross I’m also down about 1.5%. But it was mostly all at once about a week ago, as if there was a sweep that purged known bots or dead accounts or something. It hasn’t been steadily declining since then, or if so, not by much.

As election results start to come in this week, some losing candidates and supporters may claim that their election was "rigged" or "hacked". To sort fact from fiction, you have to understand how elections actually work. Here's a great reference: https://t.co/YeieXMVXBA

Here's the US Capitol, a few months after a mob of traitorous  louts tried to sack it and our system of government after they didn't like the outcome of an election. A bit scarred if you look closely, but still standing. We may not be so lucky next time. 

https://t.co/vIfeKW6I4h

Here's a photo of a train departing for parts unknown.

Absolutely not a metaphor for anything going on here.

https://t.co/6ZvmsuVmYu
If you haven't already cast your ballot, don't forget to take time off from watching the dumpster fire here to vote tomorrow.
@0x0ddc0ffee Several ways to parse that sentence, any of which sound like good stories.

I've been using Mastodon for a couple days now.  A couple (nonexpert) observations

The system as a whole functions. The major servers (that you're likely to sign up for) federate with each other, which means you can, in principle, follow and be followed just about anywhere. 1/
@ClipperChip @joepie91 I'm trying to get up to speed on technology as quickly as I can. But please be patient - I'm old.

I don't know what people are complaining about. I found setting up a Mastodon account to be no more difficult than building and installing Linux from sources.

(Seriously, it's not *that* onerous, but a lot of the same energy.)
@DeborahWyrick2 @NastyOldWomyn The onboarding experience particularly so. Once you’ve actually made it there it’s confusing for a bit, but not in ways you don’t expect.
Reminder: DST ends in the US this morning. Anything that happens between 1am and 2am, you get a do-over an hour later.
So far the main difference between here and Mastodon is that the Mastodon users seem to already know what kind of an idiot I am and don't need to ask me.
I'm https://t.co/Q8g3FNzKwW . I've not really started using it, but if that's where I end up, that's where I'll be for now.
Dual-use ambient data display and desktop art. https://t.co/B8UUgHuGre

Very much looking forward to playing with this. A cheap phase coherent array of five SDRs in a box. Interesting DF and other possibilities, potentially replacing much bigger and spendier gear. https://t.co/SLBkNNsRbz
Fighting a two-front war against your advertiser-customers and your users is some impressive 3d chess.

For the record, I'm still here. I have no plans to leave until either things demonstrably change for the worse (there's reason for pessimism) or a critical mass of people I enjoy following go somewhere else. And then I'll pack up and follow them there.

So apparently everyone (whether part of the layoff or not) is physically locked out of all Twitter facilities (through tomorrow?)

What happens if there's an operational emergency right now, like a fire or massive data center failure?
20ish years ago, midway through AT&T Labs/Research going down the drain, there was a particularly deep and inexplicably random round of layoffs. About a month or so later...

I've got friends and colleagues at Twitter, and I've watched a number of my former students land there. Many very talented and dedicated people.

This is so painful to watch.
Perhaps I should take a course in election integrity or something. I hear there's one taught at Georgetown Law. I should probably check it out. https://t.co/EfZc3h9gEP

Circulating among election misinfo is the implication that vote-by-mail/dropbox ballots are new and untested. While some jurisdictions expanded it recently, every state has long offered mail-in absentee ballots. The security and logistics are well understood. It's not new.
The single most important advance in election security of the last 5 years is the the National Academies making the "download free PDF" button more prominent on this page. https://t.co/YeieXMVpM2

Securing US elections is a complex problem often made more so by modern technology. The best overview I know of (its the main reference for my course on the subject) is this (free!) National Academies consensus study: https://t.co/YeieXMVpM2
Confession: I forgot to set my clocks to DST in last spring and seriously toyed with the idea of just being an hour late for things for eight months.
Not sure if it’s the upcoming election or the recent change in management, but I’m definitely getting a higher volume of frank assessments of my intellect and character from strangers here lately.
Oh, an X.509 certificate parsing bug. Shocked, etc.
So far, Bolsonaro appears to be petulantly refusing to concede in a more dignified and statesmanlike way than our last president who petulantly refused to concede.

Most if the value I get out of the Twitter verified system is that I can be more sure it was the actual named prominent person who just posted whatever really stupid or offensive thing I just saw retweeted.

Reports that Lula has defeated Bolsonaro in the Brazilian election.

Wishing them a peaceful and orderly transition of power.

Even the gratuitous insult doesn’t make sense. If I were “pretending to be this stupid”, that would mean by definition that my stupidity is an act. Probably he meant to ask whether I’m actually as stupid as I seem or merely pretending. https://t.co/oeTEYa5fD7
@dntlookbehindu <<shudder>>
@carlmalamud Nah. One nerd, one vote.

TIL that California has a crime called "Injuring a Wireless Communication Device".

https://t.co/OICtgCnrsi

(Fortunately for me and my increasingly clumsy electronic repair skills, it involves attempting to prevent someone from contacting a public safety agency.)
@blakereid Yeah, keeping the "wrong kind of people" from voting.

Radio nerditry: Both of the NOAA weather radio stations that serve the DC metro area (162.45 from NW DC and 162.55 from Manassas) are completely off the air. Rare opportunity for some VHF DX, though the troposphere is being uncooperative at the moment.
Now that he owns Twitter I'm sure he'll grow up and start taking things seriously.
Amazon categories. https://t.co/RGnY16dSFe

Nevada is only one example of the consequences of the baseless, relentless (and often terroristic) harassment of career election workers.

The swirl of disinformation is inviting chaos in November, which in turn will invite more disinformation and chaos.

https://t.co/UWAWVzUZNJ

Local Thai restaurant has 5 spice levels, mild, medium, spicy, Thai medium, Thai spicy.

I inadvertently checked the last box, and they called me to confirm. Grateful for the warning.
Radio nerdity: Pirate on 6950 KHz USB. "Wolverine Radio". Old time music that references radio, so far.
OK, but can Herschel Walker's so-called official badge decode secret messages? I didn't think so. https://t.co/bPTB7rhxa3
After the Herschel Walker debate, I can't help thinking of the "attache badge" from The Patriot.

Watching the hearing, I'm struck by how utterly empty the MAGA lip service about supporting law enforcement is.

At the Jan 6 rally, Trump used "law enforcement is doing a great job" as an applause line; everyone cheered. Then they marched to the Capitol and beat up the cops.

The USPS will be issuing a stamp commemorating "Women Cryptologists of WWII" next week; you can pre-order them in sheets of 20 here: https://t.co/eNMNYeha5B . It includes an encrypted message!

@blakereid Doesn’t seem to be. And I only see that it’s been edited if I click on the embedded tweet. https://t.co/UYAj3VU9o4
Oh, thank god that guy who thought he was an expert on rescuing children from underwater caves finally realized his true expertise is in brokering international peace.

Whenever time I set up a Linux box and google for the solution to some little configuration problem, the first page of search results usually consists entirely of people with the same problem being told that the solution is easily googled
@GlitchyMichael I think so.
@SnepOnSecurity @munin IAD is definitely my least favorite US airport (at least that I ever use). I sometimes forgo nonstops and fly out of DCA just to avoid it.
@SnepOnSecurity @munin I didn't appreciate just how unpleasant getting to the airport in NYC is until I moved to Philly.

@SnepOnSecurity @munin Flying out of EWR improved the trip for me a bit (living on the upper west side). Somewhat lower variance in travel time, and the NJ transit connection is tolerable. Probably the same for most of the west side of Manhattan. But elsewhere, JFK probably wins.
28000, one of the two 747s in the primary Air Force One fleet, doing a leisurely tour around DC right now, probably for a maintenance or check ride flight. https://t.co/uF205ukcVc

One of the many ways election security is frustratingly difficult is that public attention on problems tends to peak immediately before elections - when it's often too late to make even small changes to equipment and procedures.
NASA doing the ritual post-mission group hug.

I’m so glad I have so many “election integrity” activists here to remind me how unqualified I am to comment on election security (but only when my opinions are perceived as unhelpful to their cause du jour).
Week 1 of UN GA, or as I prefer to call it, “radio encryption still hard” week, wrapping up in NYC.

Loaded the release version of iOS 16 earlier today and have been running with full lockdown mode on, so far without difficulty or anything disrupting my normal usage.

You can turn it off for specific apps, but I've not needed to.
@TinkerSec Twitter remains unexplainably hard sometimes.
I've spent the last 18 hours trying to make a joke about the Pillow Guy having is phone seized by the FBI at a Hardee's and I can't come up with anything funnier than that fact.

Always amused at congressional hearings when the cameras pull back from the formal tight shots of talking heads to reveal a disorderly pile of press photographers sitting on the floor in front of the witness table like kindergartners at story time.
When I hear about the death of an elderly public figure, my brain immediately jumps to whether they lived longer than my parents and how much I would have cherished that much extra time with them.

Radio nerditry: HF/shortwave radio signal propagation is affected by the 11 year solar cycle. Closer to the peak, signals are (mostly) more likely to travel long distances. The current cycle is expected to peak around 2025. So this is a good time to explore shortwave radio.

Radio nerditry: today's callsign for the the Air Force shortwave network (11175 KHz, etc) that broadcasts encrypted messages that order (or, more often, don't order) an apocalyptic nuclear attack, is "Bad Alibi".

A bit on the nose, if you ask me.

This article, for all its detail, doesn't actually tell us very much, and suggests that the nuclear weapons docs (describing with a foreign country's nuclear defenses) might have actually been among the LESS sensitive material found.

https://t.co/63xSi74qBO
Radio nerditry: Pirate on 6925 KHz USB. Appears to be the same "Dr. Zeekey" as last night.

On the one hand, he stole classified documents, incited a violent insurrection, attempted to coerce a foreign leader for personal political gain, and ignored a deadly pandemic until it spread of control.

Radio Nerditry: with current the solar cycle in full swing, lots of faraway places are easier to hear than they’ve been in a while. Currently listening to a decent signal from the English language broadcast from BBC’s Madagascar transmitter on 9915 KHz.

There are known security vulnerabilities in many parts of our election infrastructure; that’s incontrovertibly true. But that is not the same as evidence that any election outcome was “rigged” by hacking (and in fact, there’s no evidence any actual US election has been).
